@{b}Usage@{ub}
=====

Double clicking on the GuiAmiTCP icon will load the program. From then on
all you need to do is to click on a button or pull down a menu to launch
a program.

The Menus:


OPTIONS: Has the command quit in it....enough said!!

CONFIGURATION: Has the following list of commands...

	GuiAmiTCP Config (as explained in the Configuration section)
   
        Access - Edits your INET.ACCESS so that you can decide who is
                 allowed into your computer from remote.
        Dialscript - Edits you Amitcp:db/dialscript, if you need to change
                     your password or something similar.
   
        Login Passwords - Edits the "passwd" file associated with telnet
                          and Ftp daemons.
       
        Login message - Edits your MOTD file that is displayed when you 
                        "STARTNET"
        
        Finger Messae - Edits a file in s:called .plan that is displayed 
                        when someone fingers your host/user.
                        Put something in here liek an ASCII picture or a
                        polite "STOP BLOODY FINGERING ME" message. ;)

        Edit StartNet - Edits your amitcp:bin/startnet file that is used 
                        for starting amitcp.

CONTROL: Has the following commands...

        StartNet - Executes the file Amitcp:bin/startnet.
                   Not needed if you have this in your s:user-startup.
                   Unless of course you click on StopNet.
        StopNet - Executes the file amitcp:bin/stopnet/
                  Will shut down your amitcp!!

        Connect to NET - Executes your link up file that you specified
                         in the configuration.
        Disconnect from NET - Executes your link down file that you specified
                              in the configuration.

AMITCP: Controls the amitcp commands through Gui Windows. Look in your
        amitcp guide or readme files for details on what these do.

EXTERNAL: Loads the external programs that you specified in the configuration.

WB: This allows you to execute a command like the workbench command 
    Right-Amiga and "E"

HELP: Has two commands. The first views this guide. The second is a help
      program that contacts me, the author.   

The Buttons:

These are just quicker ways of launching the external programs. 

